1
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:06,839
<i> Previously on</i> Velma...

2
00:00:06,919 --> 00:00:09,719
I'm sorry I didn't believe you
about your hallucinations.

3
00:00:09,799 --> 00:00:11,440
But, Velma, I told you this.

4
00:00:11,520 --> 00:00:14,440
Your mother didn't go missing
because you solved a mystery.

5
00:00:14,519 --> 00:00:15,360
She left us.

6
00:00:15,439 --> 00:00:16,719
La, la, la, la, la, la, la!

7
00:00:16,799 --> 00:00:18,400
Be in my office Monday morning.

8
00:00:18,479 --> 00:00:22,240
I'll tell you everything I know
about my mom, Dr. Edna Perdue.

9
00:00:22,319 --> 00:00:23,480
That book you gave me

10
00:00:23,559 --> 00:00:25,039
opened my eyes
to your inner beauty.

11
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:25,960
Wait. Really?

12
00:00:27,679 --> 00:00:28,560
Brenda?

13
00:00:31,160 --> 00:00:33,719
I'm your mother, Carroll.

14
00:00:33,799 --> 00:00:36,400
And I'm your father, Darren.

15
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,400
<i> If there's one thing</i>
<i>teen dramas get right,</i>

16
00:00:49,479 --> 00:00:52,039
<i>it's that nothing is ever</i>
<i>actually a teenager's fault.</i>

17
00:00:52,120 --> 00:00:55,199
<i>We're all really just paying</i>
<i>for the sins of our parents.</i>

18
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:56,920
<i>They're either lying to us...</i>

19
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:01,519
Oh, yeah, you discover
that polonium, Marie Curie.

20
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:02,879
<i> ...or trying</i>
<i>to change us...</i>

21
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,480
<i> ...or hiding</i>
<i>some dark family secret.</i>

22
00:01:07,559 --> 00:01:08,760
Mom!

23
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:10,080
If Velma hallucinates
while learning the truth

24
00:01:10,159 --> 00:01:11,720
about Grandma, she could die.

25
00:01:11,799 --> 00:01:13,920
Let the adults handle this,
son. Blythe?

26
00:01:13,999 --> 00:01:18,119
<i> But when it comes</i>
<i>to truly crappy parents,</i>
<i>no one beats my dad.</i>

27
00:01:18,200 --> 00:01:19,960
Dad, I need to get
to school early

28
00:01:20,039 --> 00:01:21,439
to talk to Principal Rogers.

29
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:23,319
She might have clues
about Mom's kidnapping.

30
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:24,719
That's great.

31
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:26,280
Really? But you hate
that I think she's missing.

32
00:01:26,359 --> 00:01:28,559
Are you kidding?
That's even better, Sophie.

33
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:30,199
Uh, what's happening?

34
00:01:30,280 --> 00:01:31,800
People only wear fleece

35
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:33,639
when they're looking
for startup money,
or...

36
00:01:33,720 --> 00:01:35,080
Oh, no. Going hiking.

37
00:01:35,159 --> 00:01:37,680
What's happening is
I'm taking paternity leave.

38
00:01:37,759 --> 00:01:38,959
Paternity leave?

39
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:40,599
When I was born,
you doubled your work hours.

40
00:01:40,680 --> 00:01:43,720
We know, but Amanda's birth
has made your father realize

41
00:01:43,799 --> 00:01:46,280
he needs to find
a work-life balance,

42
00:01:46,359 --> 00:01:48,920
or risk messing her up
the way he messed up--

43
00:01:48,999 --> 00:01:51,240
Well, you know.

44
00:01:56,040 --> 00:01:57,759
Hey, Velma,
want a ride to school?

45
00:01:57,840 --> 00:02:00,759
We got champagne,
AC, and the driver
has a funny story

46
00:02:00,840 --> 00:02:02,719
about how he survived
the Khmer Rouge.

47
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:04,359
Uh, sure, thanks.

48
00:02:04,440 --> 00:02:06,480
Absolutely not, Frederick.

49
00:02:06,559 --> 00:02:09,320
Unless this is your selection
for our hunt?

50
00:02:09,399 --> 00:02:11,000
No, Father. I like her now.

51
00:02:11,079 --> 00:02:12,920
Have you heard of inner beauty?

52
00:02:12,999 --> 00:02:14,720
That's a myth, you fool!

53
00:02:16,399 --> 00:02:18,359
Well, at least my relationship
with my father isn't that bad.

54
00:02:24,119 --> 00:02:25,359
Principal Rogers, I just want

55
00:02:25,439 --> 00:02:26,559
to say thank you for--

56
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:27,519
Hey, do you mind?

57
00:02:27,600 --> 00:02:28,759
Oh, yeah, mmm.

58
00:02:28,840 --> 00:02:31,199
All right. Go help Velma
not hallucinate

59
00:02:31,280 --> 00:02:32,759
while she talks to your mom.

60
00:02:32,839 --> 00:02:35,400
But don't let her
push you around.
You're your own man.

61
00:02:35,479 --> 00:02:36,439
Damn straight.

62
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:37,880
And just real quick,

63
00:02:37,959 --> 00:02:39,319
when do you need me
to have your pants mended by?

64
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:40,360
Ugh. Now.

65
00:02:40,439 --> 00:02:42,240
But lunch will be fine,
I guess.

66
00:02:42,319 --> 00:02:45,479
As I was saying, thank you
for agreeing to talk to me

67
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:47,119
about your
mad scientist mother.

68
00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:48,880
Now spill it!

69
00:02:48,960 --> 00:02:53,080
Okay. Well, buckle up,
because things are
about to get weird.

70
00:02:53,159 --> 00:02:54,679
See, in the 1970s,

71
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:58,880
my mother, Dr. Edna Perdue,
was a brilliant neurosurgeon,

72
00:02:58,959 --> 00:03:00,520
<i>who had discovered a way</i>

73
00:03:00,599 --> 00:03:03,080
<i>to keep the human brain alive</i>
<i>outside of the body.</i>

74
00:03:03,159 --> 00:03:06,039
<i> I never should have</i>
<i>been an organ donor.</i>

75
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:07,839
A woman scientist?

76
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:09,400
<i> Her work</i>
<i>caught the attention</i>

77
00:03:09,479 --> 00:03:11,839
<i>of Army General</i>
<i>Harry Meeting, who felt</i>

78
00:03:11,920 --> 00:03:14,240
<i>he could use it to spy</i>
<i>on what he believed</i>

79
00:03:14,319 --> 00:03:17,319
<i>to be the biggest threat</i>
<i>to the American way of life.</i>

80
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:20,360
Oh, let me guess. Communists?
Meat made from plants?

81
00:03:20,439 --> 00:03:21,839
-Women's sports?
-No!

82
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:23,759
<i>Meddling kids.</i>

83
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:27,000
<i>It was the 1970s, and</i>
<i>according to General Meeting,</i>

84
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:29,359
<i>meddling kids</i>
<i>were ruining everything.</i>

85
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:31,640
War's not, like, cool, man.

86
00:03:31,719 --> 00:03:34,999
<i>General Meeting had tried</i>
<i>to infiltrate these groups.</i>

87
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:37,800
But what if war is,
like, cool, man?

88
00:03:37,879 --> 00:03:39,760
<i>But the meddling kids</i>

89
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:43,519
<i>always foiled him</i>
<i>with a technique</i>
<i>called mask pulling.</i>

90
00:03:43,600 --> 00:03:46,359
<i>So, General Meeting</i>
<i>tried to infiltrate them</i>

91
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:48,120
<i>through hypnosis.</i>

92
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:51,240
<i>But this only worked</i>
<i>so long as no one ever...</i>

93
00:03:52,839 --> 00:03:54,560
<i>...snapped their fingers.</i>

94
00:03:56,600 --> 00:03:59,760
<i>So, when General Meeting</i>
<i>saw my mother's work,</i>
<i>he wondered,</i>

95
00:03:59,839 --> 00:04:01,640
<i>what if she could</i>
<i>put a soldier's brain</i>

96
00:04:01,719 --> 00:04:03,799
<i>into the head</i>
<i>of a meddling kid?</i>

97
00:04:03,880 --> 00:04:07,919
<i>He called the program</i>
<i>the Special Covert Operations</i>
<i>Brain Initiative,</i>

98
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,079
<i>or SCOOBI.</i>

99
00:04:10,160 --> 00:04:12,480
SCOOBI? And wait,
what did SCOOBI do?

100
00:04:12,559 --> 00:04:15,280
It attempted to create
the perfect spy,

101
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:17,560
by swapping people's brains.

102
00:04:17,639 --> 00:04:19,080
Oh. Did it work?

103
00:04:19,159 --> 00:04:21,199
<i> No.</i>

104
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:24,280
<i>And as the years dragged on,</i>
<i>and the pressure</i>
<i>to produce a result grew,</i>

105
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:29,039
<i>she slowly went insane.</i>

106
00:04:29,120 --> 00:04:30,839
<i>Until one day, my mom</i>

107
00:04:30,919 --> 00:04:33,080
<i>bricked up her secret lab</i>
<i>in our basement,</i>

108
00:04:33,159 --> 00:04:36,400
<i>hid her journals</i>
<i>so no one could</i>
<i>recreate her work,</i>

109
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:40,119
<i>and was committed</i>
<i>to the Crystal Cove</i>
<i>Insane Asylum.</i>

110
00:04:41,639 --> 00:04:44,279
Wow, I can't believe
that's your mom. I mean,

111
00:04:44,359 --> 00:04:46,680
playing God, removing brains.

112
00:04:46,760 --> 00:04:48,040
That's some white people shit.

113
00:04:48,119 --> 00:04:49,599
She was always a trailblazer.

114
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:51,359
But wait, my mom disappeared

115
00:04:51,440 --> 00:04:53,240
after finding
Dr. Perdue's journals,

116
00:04:53,319 --> 00:04:56,199
and the dead girls
all had their brains removed.

117
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:57,439
Could they be connected?

118
00:04:57,520 --> 00:04:59,199
Wow. For all
your personality flaws,

119
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:01,080
you're actually
a pretty good detective.

120
00:05:01,160 --> 00:05:03,879
If there is a connection
between your mom
and the dead girls,

121
00:05:03,960 --> 00:05:07,279
the key to finding it
is in this box.

122
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:17,439
You're late, Daphne.
Are you rebelling already?

123
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:20,439
As a criminal, I like it.
As your dad, knock it off.

124
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:23,960
Sorry, to get past my moms,
I had to put on
their wedding DVD.

125
00:05:24,039 --> 00:05:26,919
They'll spend all day arguing
about who let Uncle Lou dance

126
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:28,559
when they knew
he had a heart condition.

127
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:29,759
What's all this?

128
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:31,399
- Uh, that...
- Remember,

129
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:33,519
not a word about
why we really need her

130
00:05:33,599 --> 00:05:35,119
until we know we can trust her.

131
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:38,679
What happened?

132
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:40,479
Why is there a needle
in my good boob?

133
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:41,760
It's an adrenaline shot.

134
00:05:41,839 --> 00:05:43,320
Your heart stopped
from a hallucination.

135
00:05:43,400 --> 00:05:44,920
Norville, why didn't
you make me laugh?

136
00:05:44,999 --> 00:05:47,879
I tried. I did three minutes
of hilarious new stuff.

137
00:05:47,960 --> 00:05:49,239
You just didn't
get the references

138
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:50,759
because you haven't
taken calculus yet.

139
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:52,200
Velma, I'm sorry,

140
00:05:52,279 --> 00:05:54,599
but I'm not telling you
anything more about your mom

141
00:05:54,680 --> 00:05:56,279
until you stop
your hallucinations.

142
00:05:56,359 --> 00:05:58,640
The nurse only has
one adrenaline shot left,

143
00:05:58,719 --> 00:06:00,440
and I want shrimp for lunch.

144
00:06:00,519 --> 00:06:02,240
Allergies be damned!

145
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:04,759
But if you think
my mom is connected to
the serial killer in any way,

146
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:05,760
I have to know.

147
00:06:05,839 --> 00:06:06,839
Please.

148
00:06:06,919 --> 00:06:09,200
Fine. Velma, your mom--

149
00:06:11,240 --> 00:06:12,439
Norville, what am I gonna do?

150
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:14,199
I hallucinate
because I feel guilty

151
00:06:14,280 --> 00:06:16,279
about having caused my mom
to disappear.

152
00:06:16,360 --> 00:06:18,120
The only cure
is to find my mom.

153
00:06:18,199 --> 00:06:20,320
Though, I have heard
some good things
about alcoholism.

154
00:06:20,399 --> 00:06:23,480
Okay, well, uh,
when was the first time
you hallucinated?

155
00:06:23,559 --> 00:06:26,279
Hmm. It was a few days
after my mom went missing.

156
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:28,840
This is all your fault, Velma.

157
00:06:28,919 --> 00:06:30,320
Why'd you have to go

158
00:06:30,399 --> 00:06:32,719
and solve your own mystery?

159
00:06:34,440 --> 00:06:37,799
Okay, but you'd been
trying to find your mom
before that, right?

160
00:06:37,880 --> 00:06:40,240
Why didn't the hallucinations
start until then?

161
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:41,519
As a man analyzing a woman,

162
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:42,999
-can we assume menses?
-No.

163
00:06:43,080 --> 00:06:45,639
But wait, something else
did happen that day.

164
00:06:45,720 --> 00:06:49,359
My dad took me out to breakfast
for the first time ever.

165
00:06:49,439 --> 00:06:51,040
Hey, Dad. Great news.

166
00:06:51,119 --> 00:06:52,999
I've been looking for Mom,
and I think I have
some new leads--

167
00:06:53,080 --> 00:06:57,039
Velma, stop! For the last time,
your mother wasn't taken.

168
00:06:57,119 --> 00:06:58,200
She left us.

169
00:06:58,280 --> 00:06:59,800
Now, see if you can
solve the case

170
00:06:59,879 --> 00:07:03,240
of how to entertain yourself
while I make work calls.

171
00:07:03,319 --> 00:07:05,600
Wait, I've always wanted
my dad to love me more.

172
00:07:05,679 --> 00:07:08,119
Maybe the hallucinations
are my subconscious

173
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:09,879
keeping me
from looking for my mom.

174
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:12,280
Because you saying
your mom was kidnapped
upsets your dad

175
00:07:12,359 --> 00:07:14,039
and just makes it harder
for him to love you.

176
00:07:14,119 --> 00:07:15,519
Exactly! Wait!

177
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:19,440
Oh, no, I hallucinate
because I have daddy issues.

178
00:07:19,519 --> 00:07:20,360
Gross.

179
00:07:21,640 --> 00:07:23,160
Okay, so, don't search for

180
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:25,679
"Daddy issues
and teenage girls."

181
00:07:25,760 --> 00:07:27,199
And bookmark.

182
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,920
But if your
hallucinations started

183
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:30,759
because your dad
doesn't believe
your mom was kidnapped,

184
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:33,079
maybe they'd stop
if you make him believe
she was kidnapped.

185
00:07:33,160 --> 00:07:35,640
I tried,
but whenever I mention it,
he shuts me down.

186
00:07:35,720 --> 00:07:37,520
Then I have to eat a whole pie
to feel better,

187
00:07:37,599 --> 00:07:39,320
and I will die
before I give that up.

188
00:07:39,399 --> 00:07:41,080
What's another way
to cure daddy issues?

189
00:07:41,159 --> 00:07:42,239
Eh, I wouldn't know.

190
00:07:42,320 --> 00:07:43,680
The thought
of having any issues

191
00:07:43,759 --> 00:07:45,080
with my own sweet, sweet daddy
is foreign to me.

192
00:07:45,159 --> 00:07:46,639
Really? Even though
he's the one

193
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:48,200
who basically taught you
to be a beta.

194
00:07:48,279 --> 00:07:51,439
Excuse me?
My father is not a beta.

195
00:07:51,520 --> 00:07:52,760
He drives the speed limit,

196
00:07:52,839 --> 00:07:54,439
no matter how many people
are honking at him.

197
00:07:54,520 --> 00:07:55,800
Knock, knock.

198
00:07:55,880 --> 00:07:57,720
Norville, can I grab you
for a second? I need a hand

199
00:07:57,800 --> 00:07:59,320
-with some heavy lifting.
-Of course, Dad.

200
00:07:59,399 --> 00:08:02,439
Because heavy lifting is
exactly what alphas like us do.

201
00:08:02,520 --> 00:08:05,680
Thanks. We're helping
your mom's old boyfriend move.

202
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:07,119
Ah, that doesn't help.

203
00:08:08,199 --> 00:08:09,439
Ah, come on.

204
00:08:11,560 --> 00:08:13,360
Don't even think
about it, Aman.

205
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:15,159
I haven't slept in 48 hours,

206
00:08:15,240 --> 00:08:17,919
so if you're serious
about paternity leave,
then you have to realize

207
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,959
your family is more important
than your phone. Oh!

208
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:22,120
I am so posting that.

209
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:25,240
Hey, Dad, can we talk?

210
00:08:25,319 --> 00:08:26,760
You can be drunk,
if that's easier.

211
00:08:26,839 --> 00:08:28,039
What? No!

212
00:08:28,120 --> 00:08:29,599
Paternity leave applies
to all my children.

213
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:31,720
Let's go to lunch. Run!

214
00:08:31,799 --> 00:08:33,760
Aman!

215
00:08:33,839 --> 00:08:36,520
Okay. Quick lesson
in the power of crystals.

216
00:08:36,599 --> 00:08:38,479
This is angelite.

217
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:39,999
It treats anxiety

218
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:41,880
by transmuting
aberrant thoughts

219
00:08:41,960 --> 00:08:43,719
into productive cathexis.

220
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:44,919
Whoa, cool!

221
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:46,080
So, do you rub it?

222
00:08:46,159 --> 00:08:47,559
Or grind it up
and snort it at a party,

223
00:08:47,640 --> 00:08:49,000
like regular anxiety meds?

224
00:08:49,079 --> 00:08:50,119
You take it

225
00:08:50,200 --> 00:08:52,239
and bang it on your head,
real hard.

226
00:08:52,319 --> 00:08:53,879
Wait, really?

227
00:08:53,959 --> 00:08:57,320
No.
Crystals are a hoax, Daphne.

228
00:08:57,399 --> 00:08:59,400
Like vitamins, or internships.

229
00:08:59,479 --> 00:09:01,279
That's why we loved
working here so much.

230
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:03,319
Charging idiots 30 bucks
for a mystical rock

231
00:09:03,400 --> 00:09:05,600
feels like a crime,
but it's totally legal.

232
00:09:05,679 --> 00:09:07,719
So, that's why
you turned to real crime

233
00:09:07,800 --> 00:09:10,520
when the crystal market
collapsed, to chase that high.

234
00:09:10,599 --> 00:09:13,560
Yes. But the party ended
when your moms raided us.

235
00:09:13,640 --> 00:09:16,400
Sure, we got away,
but they stole you.

236
00:09:16,479 --> 00:09:17,599
And now they're gonna pay.

237
00:09:17,680 --> 00:09:19,639
Everyone's gonna pay.

238
00:09:19,720 --> 00:09:20,960
Whoa, wait. What?

239
00:09:21,039 --> 00:09:23,440
For crystals. Everyone's
